From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: usb-proxy appliance <usb-proxy@local>
Date: Thu, 2 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] musb: gadget: never flush the RX FIFO on OUT requeue;
 service a pending packet instead

musb_ep_restart() unconditionally wrote FLUSHFIFO whenever an OUT request
became the head of the queue. That is wrong twice over for gadget drivers
that requeue OUT requests outside completion context (raw-gadget servicing
reads from user space), where this path runs for every single packet:

 1. If a packet was already received into the FIFO before the request was
    queued (RXPKTRDY set), the flush silently discards data the host had
    ACKed; the host never resends it and the transfer deadlocks. This broke
    the ADB CNXN payload (device stuck "offline") on single-buffered PIO
    controllers (Allwinner sunxi). Fix: service the packet via rxstate().

 2. Even with RXPKTRDY clear there is nothing to flush -- and per the MUSB
    programming guide FLUSHFIFO is only valid while RXPKTRDY is set. The
    flush races a packet in mid-reception: the ACKed packet is either lost
    outright (it landed between the RXCSR read and the flush write) or
    delivered as a phantom zero-length packet (RXPKTRDY latches while the
    FIFO pointer is being reset, so RXCOUNT reads 0). At sustained
    high-speed bulk-OUT rates this erratically ate one 512-byte packet
    (observed directly: a WRTE payload delivered as a 0-length read
    followed by the remaining 7 of 8 packets), deadlocking large adb push
    and fastboot downloads. Fix: don't touch the FIFO; when the packet
    completes, the RX interrupt services it.

Double-buffered/large-FIFO controllers (dwc2/dwc3) hide both races.

This replaces the earlier service-pending-packet-only version of this
patch (which fixed case 1 but kept the case-2 flush) and the out-of-tree
musbfix.ko kprobe workaround before it.

Signed-off-by: usb-proxy appliance <usb-proxy@local>
---
 drivers/usb/musb/musb_gadget.c | 29 ++++++++++++++++++++++++-----
 1 file changed, 24 insertions(+), 5 deletions(-)

--- a/drivers/usb/musb/musb_gadget.c
+++ b/drivers/usb/musb/musb_gadget.c
@@ -1179,9 +1179,29 @@
 		txstate(musb, req);
 	} else {
 		csr = musb_readw(epio, MUSB_RXCSR);
-		csr |= MUSB_RXCSR_FLUSHFIFO | MUSB_RXCSR_P_WZC_BITS;
-		musb_writew(epio, MUSB_RXCSR, csr);
-		musb_writew(epio, MUSB_RXCSR, csr);
+		/*
+		 * If a packet already arrived into the FIFO before this
+		 * request was queued, service it instead of flushing it away:
+		 * the host had it ACKed, so flushing silently drops it and
+		 * deadlocks the transfer. Gadget drivers that requeue OUT
+		 * requests outside completion context (raw-gadget servicing
+		 * reads from user space) hit this window on every packet.
+		 *
+		 * With no packet pending there is nothing to flush either --
+		 * per the MUSB programming guide FLUSHFIFO is only valid
+		 * while RXPKTRDY is set. The stock unconditional flush races
+		 * a packet in mid-reception: the ACKed packet is either lost
+		 * outright (it landed between the RXCSR read above and the
+		 * flush write) or delivered as a phantom zero-length packet
+		 * (RXPKTRDY latches while the FIFO pointer is being reset, so
+		 * RXCOUNT reads 0). At sustained bulk-OUT rates this eats one
+		 * packet erratically and deadlocks ADB/fastboot streams on
+		 * single-buffered PIO controllers (Allwinner sunxi). When the
+		 * packet completes, the RX interrupt services it -- the
+		 * requeue path never needs to touch the FIFO.
+		 */
+		if (csr & MUSB_RXCSR_RXPKTRDY)
+			rxstate(musb, req);
 	}
 }
 
